(1881, 160976, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Male Wistar rats (Charles River, 300 350 g) were deeply\nanaesthetized by Equithesin (chiornembutal, 0.3 ml/100 g),\nand perfused through the heart first with saline followed by\na phosphate-buffered (PB, 0.1 M) fixative containing either\n4% paraformaldehyde, 0.2% picric acid, 0.05% glutaraldehyde\n(fixative A) for VIP[vasoactive intestinal polypeptide]-calbindin, VIP-parvalbumin and\nVIP-type la metabotropic glutamate receptor (mGluRla)\ndouble immunostaining, or 4% paraformaldehyde, 0.2%\npicric acid and 1% glutaraldehyde (fixative B) for preembedding\nVIP immunostaining combined with postembedding\nimmunogold staining for GABA [gamma aminobutyric acid]."', 'p 318 left bot', 'animal'),
(1882, 160978, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"However, VIP[vasoactive intestinal polypeptide]-positive basket cells do not contain parvalbumin (or either of the other two calcium\nbinding proteins known to label interneurons:\ncalbindin and calretinin, see accompanying paper2),\nbut co-localize another neuropeptide, cholecystokinin\n(CCK)."', 'p 331 right bot', 'data'),
(1883, 160978, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"For single VIP [vasoactive intestinal polypeptide] immunostaining\nrabbit anti-VIP, diluted 1:10,000, (16) was used as primary\nantiserum. The second layer was biotinylated anti-rabbit\nIgG (Vector, 1:200), followed by avidin biotinylatedhorseradish\nperoxidase complex (ABC, Vector 1.5h,\n1:150)."', 'p 318 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1884, 160978, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Male Wistar rats (Charles River, 300 350 g) were deeply\nanaesthetized by Equithesin (chiornembutal, 0.3 ml/100 g),\nand perfused through the heart first with saline followed by\na phosphate-buffered (PB, 0.1 M) fixative containing either\n4% paraformaldehyde, 0.2% picric acid, 0.05% glutaraldehyde\n(fixative A) for VIP[vasoactive intestinal polypeptide]-calbindin, VIP-parvalbumin and\nVIP-type la metabotropic glutamate receptor (mGluRla)\ndouble immunostaining, or 4% paraformaldehyde, 0.2%\npicric acid and 1% glutaraldehyde (fixative B) for preembedding\nVIP immunostaining combined with postembedding\nimmunogold staining for GABA [gamma aminobutyric acid]."', 'p 318 left bot', 'animal'),
(1885, 160980, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"In addition to the glutamatergic (Storm-Mathisen & Ottersen, 1984) entorhinodentate projection originating from the superficial layers of the EC [entorhinal cortex] (Steward & Scoville, 1976; Tamamaki & Nojyo, 1993), it was shown that horizontal bipolar and multipolar GABA[gamma aminobutyric acid]ergic cells (Germroth et al., 1989a, 1991) located in the same layers (I-III) of the EC form additional entorhinohippocampal projections (Germroth et al., 1989b).  The same type of calretinin-immunoposive cells were also found throughout the EC, including the deep layers, however, most of the immunopositive cells in the deep layers are not colocalized with either GAD or GABA (Miettinen et al., 1997)."', 'p 419 left top', 'data'),
(1886, 160982, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Fig. 1. Distribution of CaBP[calbindin]-immunoreactive cells in a coronal section of the rat hippocampus. Both\nprincipal and non-principal cells show CaBP immunoreactivity; it is present in cell bodies. dendrites and\naxons (the mossy ftbres) of the granule cells of the dentate gyrus, in the ìsuperficialî pyramidal cells of\nthe CA1 and CA2 regions, and in a subpopulation of non-pyramidal cells (arrows) in all layers of the\nAmmonís horn. Pyramidal cells in the CA3 subfield lack this calcium binding protein. The immunoreactive\nfibres covering the entire hilar area (h) represent local collaterals of granule cells."', 'p 794', 'data'),
(1887, 160982, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1888, 160982, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1889, 160984, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Fig. 2. Different types of CaBP[calbindin]-positive neurons in different hippocampal subfieIds. (A) Granule cells in\nstratum granulosum (s.g.) of the dentate gyrus and mossy fibres in stratum lucidurn (s.I.) of the CA3c\nregion show CaBP immunoreactivity. Arrows point to ìmisplaced" granule cells with cell bodies in\n[CA3] stratum radiatum, and dendrites extending into the molecular layer of the dentate gyrus. (B) CaBP-positive\npyramidal cells (arrowheads) are present in the ìsuperficialî pyramidal cell layer (s.p.) of the CA1 subfield.\nThe CaBP-immunoreactive non-pyramidal cells (arrows) found in all layers of the region are stained\ndarker than the pyramidal cells. (C) Arrows indicate CaBP-positive non-pvramidal cells in stratum oriens\n(s.o.) of the CA3 region. (D) CaBP-positive non-pyramidal cells (arrows) stratum radiatum (s.r.) of the\nCA3 region. The stratum lucidum with heavily stained mossy fibres is also indicted in (A), (C) and (D)."', 'p 795', 'data'),
(1890, 160984, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1891, 160984, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1892, 160986, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Mossy fibres also showed strong CaBP [calbindin]\nimmunoreactivity."', 'p 797 left bot', 'data'),
(1893, 160986, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1894, 160986, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1895, 160988, '2012-08-03 02:13:36', '"The\npattern of immunostaining for these calcium binding\nproteins and neuropeptides was similar to that described\nearlier,(22.25,28,29,32,33.35,41,46,49) therefore only a\nbrief account is given here: parvalbumin immunoreactivity\nwas found exclusively in non-pyramidal cells, these neurons were located mostly in CAI-CA3\nstratum pyramidale and oriens, and in stratum granulosum\nand hilus of the dentate gyrus."', 'p 802 left top', 'data'),
(1896, 160988, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1897, 160988, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1898, 160990, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Calretinin immunoreactivity was present\nexclusively in non-pyramidal, mostly bipolar or\nbitufted cells in all layers of the dentate gyrus and\nCAl-CA3 areas."', 'p 802 left mid', 'data'),
(1899, 160990, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1900, 160990, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1901, 160992, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"We can conclude that the\nmajority (80%) of hippocamposeptal non-pyramidal\ncells are CaBP-containing, and the NPY-immunoreactive\ncells account for only 20% of the retrogradely\nlabelled cells. However, it is not known\nyet whether there is any co-existence between\nNPY and CaBP in hippocampal non-pyramidal\ncells. The contribution of calretinin-, parvalbumin-,\nand CCK-positive neurons to the hippocamposeptal\nprojection is minor."', 'p 802 left bot', 'data'),
(1902, 160992, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"These sections were processed further to\nvisualize one of the following substances: CaBP [calbindin], parvalbumin,\ncalretinin, CCK [cholecystokinin] and NPY [neuropeptide Y] by immunocytochemistry."', 'p 797 left top', 'protocol'),
(1903, 160992, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Three adult male rats (Wistar, 250 g; LATI, Godollo,\nHungary) were used for the co-localization study, and four rats for the retrograde tracing study."', 'p 793 right bot', 'animal'),
(1904, 161008, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Earlier studies have differed\nin their descriptions of CaBP [calbindin] localization. Most have\nshown that CaBP is present in the hippocampus in most\ndentate granule cells, CA1 and CA2 pyramidal cells, but\nabsent from CA3 pyramidal cells (Jande et al., ''81; Baimbridge\nand Miller, ''82; Feldman and Christakos, ''83). Conversely,\nGarcia-Segura et al. (''84) have concluded that CaBP\nis present in both CA3 and CA1 pyramidal cells."', 'p 183 left mid', 'data'),
(1905, 161010, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"In area dentata, all processes of all granule cells appear\ndarkly stained, as do some of the interneurons of the molecular\nlayer, granule cell layer, and hilus (Fig. 3A). A few of\nthe pyramidal-shaped interneurons of the granule cell layer\nare intensely CaBP-immunoreactive and darker than adjacent\ngranule cells, but many dentate basket cells appear to\nbe devoid of CaBP-LI [calbindin-like immunoreactivity]."', 'p 186 right top', 'data'),
(1906, 161010, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1907, 161010, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1908, 161012, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"In the hippocampus ìproper,î many CA1 and CA2 pyramidal\ncells are CaBP[calbindin]-immunoreactive, as are some interneurons\nof all subfields (Figs. 3B, and C, 4A)."', 'p 186 right mid', 'data'),
(1909, 161012, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1910, 161012, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1911, 161014, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"AII CA3 pyramidal\ncells appear to be devoid of CaBP-LI [calbinding-like immunoreactivity] (Fig. 4A), even when\nsections are incubated in less dilute (1:1,000) CaBP\nantiserum."', 'p 186 right mid', 'data'),
(1912, 161014, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1913, 161014, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1914, 161016, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"The pattern of PV-LI [parvalbumin-like immunoreactivity] is unlike that of CaBP-LI [calbindin-like immunoreactivity]. No PV-LI\nis exhibited by dentate granule cells or hippocampal CA1-\nCA3 pyramidal cells although the unstained somata of\nthese principal cell populations are surrounded by a PVimmunoreactive\nfiber plexus (Figs. 1, 2)."', 'p 192 left', 'data'),
(1915, 161016, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1916, 161016, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1917, 161018, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Conversely, the\nnumerous and distinct populations of hilar somatostatinirnmunoreactive\ncells and hilar mossy cells identified in\nprevious studies (Ribak et al., ''85; Sloviter and Nilaver, ''87)\ndo not exhibit PV-LI [parvalbumin-like immunoreactivity] or CaBP-LI [calbin-like immunoreactivity]."', 'p 193 left', 'data'),
(1918, 161018, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1919, 161018, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1920, 161020, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"In area CA1, the pattern of PV-LI [parvalbumin-like immunoreactivty] is\nstrikingly dissimilar from the pattern of CaBP-LI [calbindin-like immunoreactivity] in that\nPV-LI is present almost exclusively in cells whose somata\nare in strata pyramidale and oriens or at the oriens/alveus\nborder (Fig. 7). Like CAI pyramidal cells, these PV-immunoreactive\ncells send dendrites into strata oriens and radiatum. Unlike CA1 pyramidal cells, the dendrites of PVpositive\ncells are thin, beaded, and aspinous (assuming that\nPV-immunoreactivity reveals dendritic morpohology accurately\nby filling the entire cytoplasm with DAB) and they\nform an axosomatic plexus around the pyramidal cells."', 'p 193 right', 'data'),
(1921, 161020, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1922, 161020, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1923, 161022, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Although many presumed dentate\nbasket cells exhibit CaBP[calbindin]- or PV-LI [parvalbumin-like immunoreactivity], others apparently\ndo not (there are more GABA[gamma aminobutyric acid]-positive basket cells than\nCaBP- or PV-positive basket cells), and yet all appear to be\nrelatively invulnerable to seizure activity (Sloviter, ''87)."', 'p 195 left bot', 'data'),
(1924, 161022, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Immunocytochemical staining was performed as follows.\nSections were washed in Tris (3 x 5 minutes) and then\nincubated for 30 minutes in 1.0% hydrogen peroxide in Tris\nto inactive endogenous peroxidase. Sections were then\nwashed in Tris for 5 minutes, Tris A (Tris containing 0.1%\nTriton X) for 15 minutes, and then Tris B (Tris containing\n0.1% Triton X and 0.005% BSA) for 15 minutes. This was\nfollowed by incubation overnight at 4∞C in a primary rabbit\nantiserum raised either against the 28,000-MW vitamin D-dependent\nCaBP [calbindin] from chick gut (provided by Dr. J.W. Pike)\nor against monkey cerebellar CaBP or rat muscle PV [parvalbumin] (both\nprovided by Dr. K.G. Baimbridge) at a dilution of 1:1,000 in\nTris B."', 'p 185 left bot', 'protocol'),
(1925, 161022, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Male Sprague-Dawley-descendant rats (200-350 g) were\nused in this study."', 'p 183 right top', 'animal'),
(1926, 161024, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Most VGLUT3[vesicular glutamate transporter type 3]-positive cells were reported from [CA1 and CA3] str. rad. [radiatum] (Fremeau et al., 2002) where many interneurons express CB [calbindin] (Gulyas et al., 1991) and/or CCK [cholecytokinin] (Cope et al., 2002).  Therefore, we tested VGLUT3-positive somata for the presence of CCK and CB by triple immunofluorescence labelling and quantitative confocal microscopy.  All VGLUT3-positive somata were immunoreactive for CCK (Gig. 4A-C), but not all CCK-positive somata were immunoreactive for VGLUT3 (Figs 4A and E, 5B, and 7A and B, and Table 2)."', 'p 557 left bot', 'data'),
(1927, 161024, '2012-08-03 02:13:37', '"Primary antibodies, which were reported previously, are listed and referenced in Table 1."', 'p 553 left bot', 'protocol'),
